    "summary": "The Greek philosophical tradition began in the 6th century BC with the Presocratic philosophers of Ionia (western Anatolia) — thinkers who for the first time attempted to explain the natural world through rational inquiry rather than myth, seeking a single underlying principle (arche) behind the diversity of natural phenomena. Thales of Miletus, often considered the first philosopher, proposed water as this fundamental substance; his pupil Anaximander proposed the boundless (apeiron); Anaximenes proposed air; Heraclitus proposed fire and the logos (rational principle governing change).\n\nThis move from mythos (mythological narrative) to logos (rational argument) was a revolution in intellectual method, not merely in content. The Presocratics established the practice of arguing for claims about the world on the basis of evidence and reason, critiquing competing views, and expecting others to do the same — the foundational practice of philosophy and science. The tradition continued through the Pythagoreans (who proposed mathematical structure as fundamental), the Eleatics (Parmenides' argument that change is illusory), and culminated in the Classical period with Socrates, Plato, and Aristotle. Greek philosophy's influence on Western thought is incalculable — through its transmission via Rome, medieval Islamic scholarship, and European universities, it shaped the categories and methods of virtually all Western intellectual inquiry.",
